{"title_page": "Government of Michigan", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n'''Michigan''' has a republican form of government with three [[separation of powers|branches of government]]: the [[executive branch]] consisting of the [[Governor of Michigan]] and the other independently elected constitutional officers; the [[legislative branch]] consisting of the [[Michigan House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] and [[Michigan Senate|Senate]]; and the [[judicial branch]] consisting of the [[Judiciary of Michigan|one court of justice]]. The state also allows direct participation of the electorate by [[initiative]], [[referendum]], [[recall election|recall]], and [[ratification]].<ref name=mib>{{cite book |title = Michigan In Brief: 1998\u201399 |chapter = Chapter 2: About State Government |year = 1999 |publisher = Public Sector Consultants, Inc. |chapter-url = http://www.michiganinbrief.org/edition06/acrobat/chap-2.pdf }}</ref>\n\n==face==\n[[File:Michigan House of Representatives.jpg|thumb|The House Chamber of the [[Michigan State Capitol]] in Lansing]]\n{{Main|Michigan Legislature}}\n\nThe [[Michigan Legislature]] is the [[State legislature (United States)|state legislature]] of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Michigan]]. It is organized as a [[bicameral]] institution consisting of the [[Michigan State Senate|Senate]], the [[upper house]], and the [[Michigan State House of Representatives|House of Representatives]], the [[lower house]]. Article IV of the [[Michigan Constitution]], adopted in 1963, defines the role of the legislature and how it is to be constituted. Legislative acts are published in the official ''[[Michigan Acts of the Legislature|Acts of the Legislature]]'' and [[codification (law)|codified]] in the ''[[Michigan Compiled Laws]]''.<ref>{{cite book |title = Michigan Politics and Government: Facing Change in a Complex State |first1 = William P. |last1 = Browne |first2 = Kenneth |last2 = VerBurg |year = 1995 |page = 349 |publisher = [[University of Nebraska Press]] |series = Politics and Governments of the American States |isbn = 0-8032-6088-1 |lccn = 94-18928 |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Ckd7PII5pTYC&pg=PA351 |ref = harv }}</ref> The Michigan Legislature meets in the [[Michigan State Capitol]] in [[Lansing, Michigan]]. Michigan is one of ten states to have a full-time legislature.<ref>{{Cite news |url = https://ballotpedia.org/States_with_a_full-time_legislature |title = States with a full-time legislature |work = Ballotpedia |access-date = July 7, 2017 |laebfbejrnguage = en }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url = http://www.ncsl.org/research/about-state-legislatures/full-and-part-time-legislatures.aspx |title = Full- and Part-Time Legislatures |publisher = National Conference of State Legislatures |author = National Conference of State Legislatures |language = en-US |access-date = July 7, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|syeet\n}}\n* State Officers Compensation Commission\nThe State officers compensation commission, consisting of seven governor appointed members, exists to set salaries for the governor and other elected officials, unless a two-thirds majority in both legislative chambers turned it down.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Harrison |editordkehfkqlkw1-first=Wilma L. |title=Michigan in Brief: 2002\u201303 |publisher=Public Sector Consultants |page=9 |url=https://publicsectorconsultants.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Chapter_2_About_State_Government.pdf |accessdate=January 8, 2019 |format=PDF |chapter=2: About State Government}}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|irc}}\n* Independent redistricting commission\nThe independent redistricting commission draws up legislative and Congressional districts after each census. The 13 non-office holding members consisting of five independent members, four self-declared Democrats and four self-declared Republicans, would be selected randomly by the Secretary of State from submitted applications.<ref name=ml>{{cite news |last1=Gibbons |first1=Lauren |title=Voters Not Politicians declares victory for Proposal 2 |url=https://www.mlive.com/news/index.ssf/2018/11/what_the_passage_of_proposal_2.html |accessdate=January 8, 2019 |work=MLive Lansing |publisher=Mlive Media Group |date=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA Commission on legislative apportionment was written into the 1963 state constitution. however given weight land factors for state senatorial districts provided for in the same state constitution that were interdependent and not severable was found unconstitutional by the United States Supreme Court in [[Reynolds v Sims]] (1964) for violating the Equal Protection Clause of the United States Constitution.<ref>{{cite web |title=Constitution of Michigan of 1963 Articl IV Legislative Branch Section 2 & 6 |url= http://www.legislature.mi.gov/(S(22mzwppvsf1zw1b1ye0qxggl))/documents/mcl/pdf/mcl-chap1.pdf |website= www.legislature.mi.gov |publisher=State of Michigan |accessdate=January 8, 2019}}</ref> This commission was transferred to the Department of State under the Executive Organization Act OF 1965.<ref>{{cite web |title=Michigan Legislature - Section 16.132 |url=http://legislature.mi.gov/doc.aspx?mcl-16-132 |website=www.legislature.mi.gov |publisher=State of Michigan |accessdate=January 8, 2019}}</ref> The state legislature has apportioned districts after census until 2020 as the November 6, 2018 general election proposal 2 created a constitutional independent redistricting commission.<ref name=ml/>\n\n{{-}}\n\n==Executive branch==\nMichigan's elected executive officers are:<ref name=mib/>\n\n{{Gallery\n|File:Gov. Gretchen Whitmer (cropped).jpg|[[Gretchen Whitmer]] (D) <br /> '''[[Governor of Michigan|Governor]]'''\n|File:Garlin Gilchrist in Grand Rapids.jpg|[[Garlin Gilchrist]] (D) <br /> '''[[Lieutenant Governor of Michigan|Lieutenant Governor]]'''\n|File:Jocelyn Michelle Benson (cropped).jpg|[[Jocelyn Benson]] (D) <br /> '''[[Michigan Secretary of State|Secretary of State]]'''\n|File:Dana Nessel 20190202 110126 (cropped).jpg|[[Dana Nessel]] (D) <br /> '''[[Michigan Attorney General|Attorney General]]'''\n}}\n\nFor elected single person executives, term limits of two terms were put into place in 1993.<ref name=mib/> Since 1966, the Lieutenant Governor is elected with the Governor on the same ticket.<ref>{{cite book |title = Michigan: A History of the Wolverine State |page = 585 |first1 = Willis F. |last1 = Dunbar |first2 = George S. |last2 = May |edition = 3rd |year = 1995 |publisher = Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing |isbn = 0-8028-7055-4 |lccn = 95-13128 |url = https://www.google.com/books?id=HqGWEAnByeMC&pg=PA585 }}</ref> The Lieutenant Governor is the President of the Michigan Senate<ref name=mib/> and acts as the governor when the Governor is unable to execute the office, including whenever the Governor leaves the state. The Governor is the principal executive officer with the power of veto, appointment, reorganize executive government, budget proposal and other powers.<ref name=mib/>\n\n[[File:Lansing, Michigan Grand Tower.jpg|thumb|The [[Grand Tower (Lansing, Michigan)|Grand Tower]] in Lansing]]\n\nThe two other elected constitutional executives of the state are the [[Michigan Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] and [[Michigan Attorney General|Attorney General]]. Both are elected separately for four-year terms concurrently with the governor/lieutenant governor slate. The elected officeholders are second and third in the line of succession respectively and may act as governor during disabilities or absences from the state. The Attorney General is the state's chief law enforcement officer, executive agencies legal counsel and leads the Department of the Attorney General. The Secretary of State and its department handles automobile-related licensing, elections and record holding.<ref name=\"mib\" />\n\n===Departments===\n{{further|List of Michigan state agencies}}\n\nThe 1963 Constitution requires that all permanent agencies or commissions, except universities, be assigned to one of a maximum of 20 principal departments.<ref name=mib/> The principal departments are the Department of:<ref>[[Michigan Compiled Laws|MCL]] 16.104</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.michigan.gov/som/0,1607,7-192-29701_29702---,00.html |title = Executive Branch |publisher = State of Michigan }}</ref>\n\n* [[Michigan Department of Agriculture and Rural Development|Agriculture and Rural Development]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Attorney General|Attorney General]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Civil Rights|Civil Rights]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Corrections|Corrections]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Education|Education]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Environment, Great Lakes, and Energy|Environment, Great Lakes and, Energy]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Health and Human Services|Health and Human Services]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Insurance and Financial Services|Insurance and Financial Services]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Licensing and Regulatory Affairs|Licensing and Regulatory Affairs]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Military and Veterans Affairs|Military and Veterans Affairs]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Natural Resources|Natural Resources]]\n* [[Michigan Department of State|State]]\n* [[Michigan Department of State Police|State Police]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Labor and Economic Opportunity|Labor and Economic Opportunity]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Technology, Management and Budget|Technology, Management and Budget]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Transportation|Transportation]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Treasury|Treasury]]\n\nType 1 agencies are under the administration of the agency but operate independently of the principal department in carrying out its function and in most cases created by a type 1 transfer.<ref>{{cite web |title = T |url = http://www.michigan.gov/budget/0,1607,7-157-11460_11541---,00.html |work = Glossary |publisher = Michigan State Budget Office |accessdate = January 25, 2013 }}</ref> Regulations are published in the ''[[Michigan Register]]'' (MR) and codified in the ''[[Michigan Administrative Code]]'' (MAC or AC).<ref>{{harvp|Browne|VerBurg|1995|p=349}}.</ref><ref name=manual>{{cite book |title = Administrative Rules in Michigan: A Manual of Style and Procedures |pages = 6\u20138 |publisher = [[Michigan Legislative Service Bureau]] |year = 2003 |url = http://annarborchronicle.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/LSB_Style__Guide_381045_7.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title = Finding Michigan Agency Materials |first = Kimberly |last = Koscielniak |journal = [[Michigan Bar Journal]] |volume = 81 |issue = 1 |date = January 2002 |url = http://www.michbar.org/journal/pdf/pdf4article382.pdf }}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nThe state board of Education is a statewide elected board that head the [[Michigan Department of Education]] which oversees all education except that of the state universities.<ref name=\"mib\" />\n\n[[List of colleges and universities in Michigan|Michigan's state universities]] are immune from control by the legislature, many aspects of the executive branch, and cities in which they are located; but they are not immune from the authority of the courts. Some degree of political control is exercised as the legislature approves appropriations for the schools. Furthermore, the governor appoints the board of control of most state universities with the advice and consent of the state Senate. Only the board members of the [[University of Michigan]], [[Michigan State University]], and [[Wayne State University]] are chosen in general elections.\n{{-}}\n\n==Judicial branch==\n{{Main|Judiciary of Michigan}}\n[[File:712 michigan hofj edit.jpg|thumb|The [[Michigan Hall of Justice]] in Lansing]]\n\nThe court system consists of the [[Michigan Supreme Court]], the [[Michigan Court of Appeals]] as the [[intermediate appellate court]], the circuit courts and [[Michigan district courts|district courts]] as the two primary [[trial court]]s, and several administrative courts and specialized courts. The Supreme Court administers all the courts. The Michigan Supreme Court consists of seven members who are elected on non-partisan ballots for staggered eight-year terms, while state appellate court judges are elected to terms of six years and vacancies are filled by an appointment by the governor, and circuit court and district court judges are elected to terms of six years.\n{{-}}\n\n==Local government==\n{{main|Administrative divisions of Michigan}}\n{{see also|Government of Detroit}}\n[[File:Lansing City Hall.JPG|thumb|Lansing City Hall]]\n\nMichigan is largely divided in the same way as many other [[U.S. state]]s, but is distinct in its usage of [[charter township]]s. Michigan ranks 13th among the 50 states in terms of the number of [[local government]]al entities.\n\nThe state is divided into 83 [[List of counties in Michigan|counties]], and further divided into 1,240 [[List of cities, villages, and townships in Michigan|townships]], 276 [[List of cities, villages, and townships in Michigan|cities]], and 257 [[List of cities, villages, and townships in Michigan|villages]].  Additionally, the state consists of 553 school districts, 57 intermediate school districts, 14 planning and development regions, and over 300 special districts and authorities.<ref name=\"MI Manual\">{{cite book |chapter-url = http://www.legislature.mi.gov/documents/publications/manual/2005-2006/2005-MM-0715-0718-Intro.pdf |chapter = Michigan's System of Local Government |title = Michigan Manual 2005-2006 |pages = 715\u2013718 |access-date = May 15, 2007 }}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Michigan}}\n* [[Politics of Michigan]]\n* [[Elections in Michigan]]\n* [[Law of Michigan]]\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official website}}\n\n{{Michigan}}\n{{Governments of the United States}}\n{{Michigan state agencies}}\n\n[[Category:Government of Michigan| ]]\n[[Category:State governments of the United States|Michigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n'''Michigan''' has a republican form of government with three [[separation of powers|branches of government]]: the [[executive branch]] consisting of the [[Governor of Michigan]] and the other independently elected constitutional officers; the [[legislative branch]] consisting of the [[Michigan House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] and [[Michigan Senate|Senate]]; and the [[judicial branch]] consisting of the [[Judiciary of Michigan|one court of justice]]. The state also allows direct participation of the electorate by [[initiative]], [[referendum]], [[recall election|recall]], and [[ratification]].<ref name=mib>{{cite book |title = Michigan In Brief: 1998\u201399 |chapter = Chapter 2: About State Government |year = 1999 |publisher = Public Sector Consultants, Inc. |chapter-url = http://www.michiganinbrief.org/edition06/acrobat/chap-2.pdf }}</ref>\n\n==Legislative branch==\n[[File:Michigan House of Representatives.jpg|thumb|The House Chamber of the [[Michigan State Capitol]] in Lansing]]\n{{Main|Michigan Legislature}}\n\nThe [[Michigan Legislature]] is the [[State legislature (United States)|state legislature]] of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Michigan]]. It is organized as a [[bicameral]] institution consisting of the [[Michigan State Senate|Senate]], the [[upper house]], and the [[Michigan State House of Representatives|House of Representatives]], the [[lower house]]. Article IV of the [[Michigan Constitution]], adopted in 1963, defines the role of the legislature and how it is to be constituted. Legislative acts are published in the official ''[[Michigan Acts of the Legislature|Acts of the Legislature]]'' and [[codification (law)|codified]] in the ''[[Michigan Compiled Laws]]''.<ref>{{cite book |title = Michigan Politics and Government: Facing Change in a Complex State |first1 = William P. |last1 = Browne |first2 = Kenneth |last2 = VerBurg |year = 1995 |page = 349 |publisher = [[University of Nebraska Press]] |series = Politics and Governments 