ected single person executives, term limits of two terms were put into place in 1993.<ref name=mib/> Since 1966, the Lieutenant Governor is elected with the Governor on the same ticket.<ref>{{cite book |title = Michigan: A History of the Wolverine State |page = 585 |first1 = Willis F. |last1 = Dunbar |first2 = George S. |last2 = May |edition = 3rd |year = 1995 |publisher = Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing |isbn = 0-8028-7055-4 |lccn = 95-13128 |url = https://www.google.com/books?id=HqGWEAnByeMC&pg=PA585 }}</ref> The Lieutenant Governor is the President of the Michigan Senate<ref name=mib/> and acts as the governor when the Governor is unable to execute the office, including whenever the Governor leaves the state. The Governor is the principal executive officer with the power of veto, appointment, reorganize executive government, budget proposal and other powers.<ref name=mib/>\n\n[[File:Lansing, Michigan Grand Tower.jpg|thumb|The [[Grand Tower (Lansing, Michigan)|Grand Tower]] in Lansing]]\n\nThe two other elected constitutional executives of the state are the [[Michigan Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] and [[Michigan Attorney General|Attorney General]]. Both are elected separately for four-year terms concurrently with the governor/lieutenant governor slate. The elected officeholders are second and third in the line of succession respectively and may act as governor during disabilities or absences from the state. The Attorney General is the state's chief law enforcement officer, executive agencies legal counsel and leads the Department of the Attorney General. The Secretary of State and its department handles automobile-related licensing, elections and record holding.<ref name=\"mib\" />\n\n===Departments===\n{{further|List of Michigan state agencies}}\n\nThe 1963 Constitution requires that all permanent agencies or commissions, except universities, be assigned to one of a maximum of 20 principal departments.<ref name=mib/> The principal departments are the Department of:<ref>[[Michigan Compiled Laws|MCL]] 16.104</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.michigan.gov/som/0,1607,7-192-29701_29702---,00.html |title = Executive Branch |publisher = State of Michigan }}</ref>\n\n* [[Michigan Department of Agriculture and Rural Development|Agriculture and Rural Development]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Attorney General|Attorney General]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Civil Rights|Civil Rights]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Corrections|Corrections]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Education|Education]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Environment, Great Lakes, and Energy|Environment, Great Lakes and, Energy]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Health and Human Services|Health and Human Services]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Insurance and Financial Services|Insurance and Financial Services]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Licensing and Regulatory Affairs|Licensing and Regulatory Affairs]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Military and Veterans Affairs|Military and Veterans Affairs]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Natural Resources|Natural Resources]]\n* [[Michigan Department of State|State]]\n* [[Michigan Department of State Police|State Police]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Labor and Economic Opportunity|Labor and Economic Opportunity]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Technology, Management and Budget|Technology, Management and Budget]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Transportation|Transportation]]\n* [[Michigan Department of Treasury|Treasury]]\n\nType 1 agencies are under the administration of the agency but operate independently of the principal department in carrying out its function and in most cases created by a type 1 transfer.<ref>{{cite web |title = T |url = http://www.michigan.gov/budget/0,1607,7-157-11460_11541---,00.html |work = Glossary |publisher = Michigan State Budget Office |accessdate = January 25, 2013 }}</ref> Regulations are published in the ''[[Michigan Register]]'' (MR) and codified in the ''[[Michigan Administrative Code]]'' (MAC or AC).<ref>{{harvp|