re elected on non-partisan ballots for staggered eight-year terms, while state appellate court judges are elected to terms of six years and vacancies are filled by an appointment by the governor, and circuit court and district court judges are elected to terms of six years.\n{{-}}\n\n==Local government==\n{{main|Administrative divisions of Michigan}}\n{{see also|Government of Detroit}}\n[[File:Lansing City Hall.JPG|thumb|Lansing City Hall]]\n\nMichigan is largely divided in the same way as many other [[U.S. state]]s, but is distinct in its usage of [[charter township]]s. Michigan ranks 13th among the 50 states in terms of the number of [[local government]]al entities.\n\nThe state is divided into 83 [[List of counties in Michigan|counties]], and further divided into 1,240 [[List of cities, villages, and townships in Michigan|townships]], 276 [[List of cities, villages, and townships in Michigan|cities]], and 257 [[List of cities, villages, and townships in Michigan|villages]].  Additionally, the state consists of 553 school districts, 57 intermediate school districts, 14 planning and development regions, and over 300 special districts and authorities.<ref name=\"MI Manual\">{{cite book |chapter-url = http://www.legislature.mi.gov/documents/publications/manual/2005-2006/2005-MM-0715-0718-Intro.pdf |chapter = Michigan's System of Local Government |title = Michigan Manual 2005-2006 |pages = 715\u2013718 |access-date = May 15, 2007 }}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Michigan}}\n* [[Politics of Michigan]]\n* [[Elections in Michigan]]\n* [[Law of Michigan]]\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official website}}\n\n{{Michigan}}\n{{Governments of the United States}}\n{{Michigan state agencies}}\n\n[[Category:Government of Michigan| ]]\n[[Category:State governments of the United States|Michigan]]\n", "name_user": "2601:600:807f:24b0:6c96:139c:8bd7:3a1a", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.or